ry Center | date=Spring 2014 | volume=8 | issue=2 | pp=1,3,6 | url=http://www.dekalbhistory.org/documents/Spring2014Newsletter_000.pdf | access-date=May 24, 2017 | ref = {{harvid|DHC|2014a}} | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218085118/http://www.dekalbhistory.org/documents/Spring2014Newsletter_000.pdf | archive-date=December 18, 2015 }}\n* {{cite journal|title=The Swanton House Now | journal=Times of DeKalb | publisher=DeKalb History Center | date=Summer 2014 | volume=8 | issue=3 | pp=1,3,4 | url=http://www.dekalbhistory.org/documents/Summer2014Newsletter.pdf | access-date=May 24, 2017 | ref = {{harvid|DHC|2014b}} | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218170631/http://www.dekalbhistory.org/documents/Summer2014Newsletter.pdf | archive-date=December 18, 2015 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Swanton House}}\n* [https://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=9364 The Swanton House] [[historical marker]] with photos\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in DeKalb County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Decatur, Georgia]]\n", "name_user": "A.C.Butner", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swanton_House"}
{"title_page": "L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Mexican criminal}}\n{{Spanish name|Marroqu\u00edn|Garc\u00eda}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda\n|image         = File:Lictor Hazael Marroquin Garcia.PNG\n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda\n|birth_date    = {{birth based on age as of date|35|1978|10|13|noage=1}}\n|birth_place   = [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], [[Tamaulipas]], [[Mexico]]\n|death_date    = 7 May 1985 (aged 42\u201343)\n|death_place   = Matamoros, Tamaulipas, Mexico\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = Mexican\n|ethnicity     = \n|citizenship   =\n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = \n|education     =\n|alma_mater    = \n|employer      = \n|occupation    = \n|home_town     = \n|title         =\n|salary        =\n|networth      =\n|height        = \n|weight        = \n|term          = \n|predecessor   = \n|successor     = \n|party         =\n|boards        =\n|religion      =\n| criminal_charge    ={{hlist|Transporting stolen vehicles using foreign commerce}}\n| criminal_penalty   = 5 years (sentence suspended)\n| criminal_status    = Convicted\n|spouse        = Beatriz Martha Hern\u00e1ndez Simental\n|partner       = \n|children      = \n|parents       = \n|relations     =\n|callsign      =\n|signature     =\n|website       =\n|footnotes     = Convicted by [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas]] in [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]]\n}}\n'''L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8li\u0261.to\u027e a\u02c8sa.el maro\u02c8k\u0129n \u0261ar\u02c8sia|}}; c. 1942 \u2013 7 May 1985) was a Mexican criminal and convicted vehicle thief. He was the best friend of drug kingpin [[Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego]], the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], a criminal group based in [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico. In 1978, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was indicted by the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|U.S. District Court of the Southern District of Texas]] in [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] for transporting stolen vehicles from the U.S. into Mexico. He was indicted along with seventeen other people, including Garc\u00eda Abrego, who was a low-level criminal at that time. Convicted in 1979, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda had his sentence suspended and was deported back to Mexico. He died of [[cirrhosis]] in 1985.\n\n==Early life==\nL\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was born in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], Mexico, on {{birth based on age as of date|35|1978|10|13|noage=1}}.<ref name=\"dHDj\" /> His parents were Ovidio Marroqu\u00edn Salinas and Evangelina Garc\u00eda de Marroqu\u00edn.<ref name=\"OPDd\" /> He had two brothers, C\u00e9sar Ovidio and Cid Mario.<ref name=\"BKDded\" /> Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was the best friend of drug kingpin [[Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego]], the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], a criminal group based in [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico.<ref name=\"Bidew5\" /><ref name=\"PVepP\" /> Though usually reserved with others, Garc\u00eda Abrego was very close to Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda and spoke to him about personal matters.{{Sfn|Garc\u00eda Cabrera|2012|p=293}} Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda's mother said she remembered Garc\u00eda Abrego as a \"good boy\".<ref name=\"Bidew5\" />\n\n==Criminal career==\nAccording to an indictment sworn in by a grand jury of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas]] in [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] on 8&nbsp;November 1978, sometime between 2&nbsp;September and 11&nbsp;October 1978, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda and seventeen other individuals, including Garc\u00eda Abrego, unlawfully transported stolen vehicles from the U.S. into Mexico in violation of a federal code dealing with [[Title 18 of the United States Code|illegal interstate or foreign commerce]].<ref name=\"dHDj\" />{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=1-2}} In total, six [[Semi-trailer truck|tractor trailer trucks]], three truck trailers, and {{Convert|44,833|lb|kg ST|abbr=on}} of stainless steel coils and skids were stolen from [[San Antonio]], [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] and [[Houston]]. All of these goods were transported to Brownsville, where most were then smuggled and sold in Mexico.<ref name=\"dHDj\" /> The indictment specified that on or around 10&nbsp;September, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda met with Garc\u00eda Abrego, David Lee Kuehn, Richard Wayne Cotton, and Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez (\"Chuy\" or \"Chema\") in Brownsville to coordinate the transfer of a 1977 [[Kenworth]] Truck Tractor. The vehicle was stolen by Richard Wayne Cotton, Thomas Scott Bates (\"Slick\"), and Richard Cook in Houston. Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda drove the tractor from Brownsville to Mexico on or around that date.{{efn|The tractor had [[Vehicle registration plates of Texas|Texas license plate number]] R34330.{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=2-3}}}}{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=2-3}}      \n\nOn or around 11&nbsp;October, another vehicle was stolen; Cotton, Bates and Gregory Nathan Fee stole a 1977 Kenworth Truck Tractor and a flat-bed trailer in San Antonio and transported them to Brownsville.<ref name=\"bD3ho\" />{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=4-5}} The indictment stated that Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda met with Garc\u00eda Abrego, Gonz\u00e1lez, Fred B. Rendon, Jr., and [[Sa\u00fal Hern\u00e1ndez Rivera]] in Brownsville to discuss arrangements. U.S. authorities stated that Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda and the other co-defendants knew the vehicles were stolen.{{efn|The tractor had [[vehicle identification number]] (VIN) P158381.{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=4-5}}}}{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=4-5}} The tractors were owned by a man identified as Leroy Eash; their loss totaled US$10,000.<ref name=\"Mjd33\" /> The U.S. attorneys for the case were J.A. \"Tony\" Canales and Charles Lewis; the court's clerk was V. Bailey Thomas and the jury foreman was James D. Cook.{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=9}} The investigation was led by the [[Texas Department of Public Safety]] with the assistance of local [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) officials.<ref name=\"Mjd33\" /> When the indictment was issued, Garc\u00eda Abrego was a low-level criminal and was not the leader of the Gulf Cartel.<ref name=\"95xqH\" /><ref name=\"7iX6R\" />       \n\nOn 13&nbsp;October, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was arrested in Brownsville, along with Rend\u00f3n and Kuehn. [[Justice of the peace|Justice of Peace]] Alex Perez set a US$5,000 [[Bail in the United States|bond]] for all three individuals. Their defense asked the official to reduce the bond amount to something more \"reasonable\", but Perez rejected the motion, saying that the bond he requested was recommended by the State of Texas. Following discussions over the bond, Perez discovered that Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda did not understand English, so he proceeded to explain the arrangement in Spanish.<ref name=\"Mjd33\" /> On 4&nbsp;March 1979, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was convicted of transporting stolen vehicles using foreign commerce and was sentenced to five years in prison. However, his conviction included an execution of sentence suspended (ESS), which cancelled his sentence as long as he did not violate any conditions set during the term of his [[probation]]. He was given five-year's probation without supervision. Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was [[Deportation and removal from the United States|deported back to Mexico]] shortly after the announcement of his conviction.<ref name=\"wHWh4\" />\n\n==Death==\nAt 17:00&nbsp;hours on 7&nbsp;May 1985,{{efn|Another source stated that he died on 22 August 1985.<ref name=\"Bidew5\" />}} Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda died of [[cirrhosis]] in Matamoros. According to details provided by Dr. Jos\u00e9 Luis Mart\u00ednez Ortiz, he suffered from [[esophageal varices]] and bled from a massive proximal digestive tube.{{efn|His death certificate was registered by government officials Jos\u00e9 de la Cruz Flores and Alicia D. de R\u00edos on 13&nbsp;May. Witnesses J. Antonio Sol\u00eds and Antonio Mel\u00e9ndez signed off and confirmed his death.<ref name=\"OPDd\" />}}<ref name=\"OPDd\" /> His family held a wake at the Lozano funeral home. He was buried in Jard\u00edn cemetery the following day. At the time of his death, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was married to Beatriz Martha Hern\u00e1ndez Simental.<ref name=\"OPDd\" /><ref name=\"BKDded\" /> Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda's mother said that Garc\u00eda Abrego was deeply saddened by his death and cried \"inconsolably\" at one of his ranches. Garc\u00eda Abrego sent flowers to Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda's grave every year on his death date and on the [[Day of the Dead]] until his arrest in 1996.<ref name=\"Bidew5\" /> Over the years, Garc\u00eda Abrego befriended a man named [[Luis Medrano Garc\u00eda]], who later became a high-ranking Gulf Cartel member. Those close to Garc\u00eda Abrego said that he became more reserved with others, including people with whom he was also friends, after Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda died.{{Sfn|Garc\u00eda Cabrera|2012|p=293}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mexican Drug War]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1=2|refs=\n<ref name=\"dHDj\">{{Cite news|last=Salter|first=Becky|url=https://access.newspaperarchive.com/|title=Fed Grand Jury Indicts 18|date=9 November 1978|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=|url-status=live|via=[[NewspaperArchive]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"OPDd\">{{Cite book|last=de R\u00edos|first=Alicia D.|title=Acta de Difunci\u00f3n (No. de Control 035085)|date=13 May 1985|publisher=Registro Civil, Gobierno de Tamaulipas|year=|isbn=|location=Matamoros, Tamaulipas|pages=|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Bidew5\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.proceso.com.mx/171227/en-los-pasados-seis-anos-el-cartel-del-golfo-introdujo-cerca-de-750-toneladas-de-cocaina-pura-a-estados-unidos|title=En los pasados seis a\u00f1os, el C\u00e1rtel del Golfo introdujo cerca de 750 toneladas de coca\u00edna pura a Estados Unidos|date=20 January 1996|work=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Spanish|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330114934/https://www.proceso.com.mx/171227/en-los-pasados-seis-anos-el-cartel-del-golfo-introdujo-cerca-de-750-toneladas-de-cocaina-pura-a-estados-unidos|archivedate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Mjd33\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://access.newspaperarchive.com/|title=Three Men Charged In Truck Theft|date=13 October 1978|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=|url-status=live|via=[[NewspaperArchive]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bD3ho\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://access.newspaperarchive.com/|title=Expidi\u00f3 Procesos Un Gran Jurado Federal En Bville|date=10 November 1978|work=[[The Brownsville Herald|El Heraldo de Brownsville]]|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Spanish|via=[[NewspaperArchive]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"95xqH\">{{Cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|url=https://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/local/aug-garcia-abrego-escaped-fbi-prosecutors/article_ff105e68-88d2-5600-8e04-7174b2797126.html|title=Garcia Abrego escaped FBI, prosecutors|date=30 August 1995|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215005929/https://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/local/aug-garcia-abrego-escaped-fbi-prosecutors/article_ff105e68-88d2-5600-8e04-7174b2797126.html|archivedate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"7iX6R\">{{Cite news|last=Dillon|first=Sam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/12/world/victory-deceit-special-report-bribes-publicity-mark-fall-mexican-drug-lord.html|title=Victory or Deceit? \u2013 Bribes and Publicity Mark Fall of Mexican Drug Lord|date=12 May 1996|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=|url-status=live|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"wHWh4\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://access.newspaperarchive.com/|title=Cameron State, Federal Court Records: District Court Criminal Judgements|date=4 March 1979|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|via=[[NewspaperArchive]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BKDded\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Obituario: Lictor Hazahel Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda|date=8 May 1985|work=El Bravo|access-date=|url-status=live|location=Matamoros, Tamaulipas|page=5|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"PVepP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/mexico-organized-crime-news/gulf-cartel-profile/|title=Gulf Cartel|last=|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=|publisher=[[InSight Crime]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401151723/https://www.insightcrime.org/mexico-organized-crime-news/gulf-cartel-profile/|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Garc\u00eda Cabrera|first=Jose Luis|year=2012|title=1920\u20132000 \u00a1El Pastel! Parte Dos|publisher=Palibrio|isbn=978-1463337018|url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=46FE6lfgh9YC&pg|language=Spanish|ref=harv}}\n\n*{{Cite book|last=Thomas|first=V. Bailey|title=United States of America v. Lictor Hazael Marroquin-Garcia|publisher=[[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas]]|year=1978|isbn=|location=Brownsville, Texas|ref=harv}}\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n[[Category:1940s births]]\n[[Category:Gulf Cartel members]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:People deported from the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of theft]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n[[Category:People from Matamoros, Tamaulipas]]\n[[Category:Mexican people imprisoned abroad]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Mexican criminal}}\n{{Spanish name|Marroqu\u00edn|Garc\u00eda}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda\n|image         = File:Lictor Hazael Marroquin Garcia.PNG\n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda\n|birth_date    = {{birth based on age as of date|35|1978|10|13|noage=1}}\n|birth_place   = [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], [[Tamaulipas]], [[Mexico]]\n|death_date    = 7 May 1985 (aged 42\u201343)\n|death_place   = Matamoros, Tamaulipas, Mexico\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = Mexican\n|ethnicity     = \n|citizenship   =\n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = \n|education     =\n|alma_mater    = \n|employer      = \n|occupation    = \n|home_town     = \n|title         =\n|salary        =\n|networth      =\n|height        = \n|weight        = \n|term          = \n|predecessor   = \n|successor     = \n|party         =\n|boards        =\n|religion      =\n| criminal_charge    ={{hlist|Transporting stolen vehicles using foreign commerce}}\n| criminal_penalty   = 5 years (sentence suspended)\n| criminal_status    = Convicted\n|spouse        = Beatriz Martha Hern\u00e1ndez Simental\n|partner       = \n|children      = \n|parents       = \n|relations     =\n|callsign      =\n|signature     =\n|website       =\n|footnotes     = Convicted by [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas]] in [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]]\n}}\n'''L\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8li\u0261.to\u027e a\u02c8sa.el maro\u02c8k\u0129n \u0261ar\u02c8sia|}}; c. 1942 \u2013 7 May 1985) was a Mexican criminal and convicted vehicle thief. He was the best friend of drug kingpin [[Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego]], the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], a criminal group based in [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico. In 1978, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was indicted by the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|U.S. District Court of the Southern District of Texas]] in [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] for transporting stolen vehicles from the U.S. into Mexico. He was indicted along with seventeen other people, including Garc\u00eda Abrego, who was a low-level criminal at that time. Convicted in 1979, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda had his sentence suspended and was deported back to Mexico. He died of [[cirrhosis]] in 1985.\n\n==Early life==\nL\u00edctor Hazael Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was born in [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]], Mexico, on {{birth based on age as of date|35|1978|10|13|noage=1}}.<ref name=\"dHDj\" /> His parents were Ovidio Marroqu\u00edn Salinas and Evangelina Garc\u00eda de Marroqu\u00edn.<ref name=\"OPDd\" /> He had two brothers, C\u00e9sar Ovidio and Cid Mario.<ref name=\"BKDded\" /> Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was the best friend of drug kingpin [[Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego]], the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], a criminal group based in [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico.<ref name=\"Bidew5\" /><ref name=\"PVepP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/mexico-organized-crime-news/gulf-cartel-profile/|title=Gulf Cartel|last=|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=|publisher=[[InSight Crime]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401151723/https://www.insightcrime.org/mexico-organized-crime-news/gulf-cartel-profile/|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> Though usually reserved with others, Garc\u00eda Abrego was very close to Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda and spoke to him about personal matters.{{Sfn|Garc\u00eda Cabrera|2012|p=293}} Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda's mother said she remembered Garc\u00eda Abrego as a \"good boy\".<ref name=\"Bidew5\" />\n\n==Criminal career==\nAccording to an indictment sworn in by a grand jury of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas]] in [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] on 8&nbsp;November 1978, sometime between 2&nbsp;September and 11&nbsp;October 1978, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda and seventeen other individuals, including Garc\u00eda Abrego, unlawfully transported stolen vehicles from the U.S. into Mexico in violation of a federal code dealing with [[Title 18 of the United States Code|illegal interstate or foreign commerce]].<ref name=\"dHDj\" />{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=1-2}} In total, six [[Semi-trailer truck|tractor trailer trucks]], three truck trailers, and {{Convert|44,833|lb|kg ST|abbr=on}} of stainless steel coils and skids were stolen from [[San Antonio]], [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] and [[Houston]]. All of these goods were transported to Brownsville, where most were then smuggled and sold in Mexico.<ref name=\"dHDj\" /> The indictment specified that on or around 10&nbsp;September, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda met with Garc\u00eda Abrego, David Lee Kuehn, Richard Wayne Cotton, and Jes\u00fas Mar\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez (\"Chuy\" or \"Chema\") in Brownsville to coordinate the transfer of a 1977 [[Kenworth]] Truck Tractor. The vehicle was stolen by Richard Wayne Cotton, Thomas Scott Bates (\"Slick\"), and Richard Cook in Houston. Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda drove the tractor from Brownsville to Mexico on or around that date.{{efn|The tractor had [[Vehicle registration plates of Texas|Texas license plate number]] R34330.{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=2-3}}}}{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=2-3}}      \n\nOn or around 11&nbsp;October, another vehicle was stolen; Cotton, Bates and Gregory Nathan Fee stole a 1977 Kenworth Truck Tractor and a flat-bed trailer in San Antonio and transported them to Brownsville.<ref name=\"bD3ho\" />{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=4-5}} The indictment stated that Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda met with Garc\u00eda Abrego, Gonz\u00e1lez, Fred B. Rendon, Jr., and [[Sa\u00fal Hern\u00e1ndez Rivera]] in Brownsville to discuss arrangements. U.S. authorities stated that Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda and the other co-defendants knew the vehicles were stolen.{{efn|The tractor had [[vehicle identification number]] (VIN) P158381.{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=4-5}}}}{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=4-5}} The tractors were owned by a man identified as Leroy Eash; their loss totaled US$10,000.<ref name=\"Mjd33\" /> The U.S. attorneys for the case were J.A. \"Tony\" Canales and Charles Lewis; the court's clerk was V. Bailey Thomas and the jury foreman was James D. Cook.{{Sfn|Thomas|1978|p=9}} The investigation was led by the [[Texas Department of Public Safety]] with the assistance of local [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) officials.<ref name=\"Mjd33\" /> When the indictment was issued, Garc\u00eda Abrego was a low-level criminal and was not the leader of the Gulf Cartel.<ref name=\"95xqH\" /><ref name=\"7iX6R\" />       \n\nOn 13&nbsp;October, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was arrested in Brownsville, along with Rend\u00f3n and Kuehn. [[Justice of the peace|Justice of Peace]] Alex Perez set a US$5,000 [[Bail in the United States|bond]] for all three individuals. Their defense asked the official to reduce the bond amount to something more \"reasonable\", but Perez rejected the motion, saying that the bond he requested was recommended by the State of Texas. Following discussions over the bond, Perez discovered that Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda did not understand English, so he proceeded to explain the arrangement in Spanish.<ref name=\"Mjd33\" /> On 4&nbsp;March 1979, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was convicted of transporting stolen vehicles using foreign commerce and was sentenced to five years in prison. However, his conviction included an execution of sentence suspended (ESS), which cancelled his sentence as long as he did not violate any conditions set during the term of his [[probation]]. He was given five-year's probation without supervision. Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was [[Deportation and removal from the United States|deported back to Mexico]] shortly after the announcement of his conviction.<ref name=\"wHWh4\" />\n\n==Death==\nAt 17:00&nbsp;hours on 7&nbsp;May 1985,{{efn|Another source stated that he died on 22 August 1985.<ref name=\"Bidew5\" />}} Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda died of [[cirrhosis]] in Matamoros. According to details provided by Dr. Jos\u00e9 Luis Mart\u00ednez Ortiz, he suffered from [[esophageal varices]] and bled from a massive proximal digestive tube.{{efn|His death certificate was registered by government officials Jos\u00e9 de la Cruz Flores and Alicia D. de R\u00edos on 13&nbsp;May. Witnesses J. Antonio Sol\u00eds and Antonio Mel\u00e9ndez signed off and confirmed his death.<ref name=\"OPDd\" />}}<ref name=\"OPDd\" /> His family held a wake at the Lozano funeral home. He was buried in Jard\u00edn cemetery the following day. At the time of his death, Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda was married to Beatriz Martha Hern\u00e1ndez Simental.<ref name=\"OPDd\" /><ref name=\"BKDded\" /> Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda's mother said that Garc\u00eda Abrego was deeply saddened by his death and cried \"inconsolably\" at one of his ranches. Garc\u00eda Abrego sent flowers to Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda's grave every year on his death date and on the [[Day of the Dead]] until his arrest in 1996.<ref name=\"Bidew5\" /> Over the years, Garc\u00eda Abrego befriended a man named [[Luis Medrano Garc\u00eda]], who later became a high-ranking Gulf Cartel member. Those close to Garc\u00eda Abrego said that he became more reserved with others, including people with whom he was also friends, after Marroqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda died.{{Sfn|Garc\u00eda Cabrera|2012|p=293}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mexican Drug War]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1=2|refs=\n<ref name=\"dHDj\">{{Cite news|last=Salter|first=Becky|url=https://access.newspaperarchive.com/|title=Fed Grand Jury Indicts 18|date=9 November 1978|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|access-date=|url-status=live|via=[[NewspaperArchive]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"OPDd\">{{Cite book|last=de R\u00edos|first=Alicia D.|title=Acta de Difunci\u00f3n (No. de Control 035085)|date=13 May 1985|publisher=Registro Civil, Gobierno de Tamaulipas|year=|isbn=|location=Matamoros, Tamaulipas|pages=|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n<